      {
        "id": "_context",
        "title": "Context",
        "level": 2,
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "html": "Domain repositories return <code>CompletableFuture</code> (Java SE standard async), but Spring Boot 4 WebFlux uses <code>Mono</code>/<code>Flux</code> for reactive composition. The boundary between these two async models must be explicit and manageable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "_decision",
        "title": "Decision",
        "level": 2,
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "list",
            "style": "ulist",
            "items": [
              {
                "text": "<strong>Domain</strong>: all repository interfaces return <code>CompletableFuture<Void></code> or <code>CompletableFuture<Optional<T>></code>",
                "blocks": []
              },
              {
                "text": "<strong>Application</strong>: services bridge CompletableFuture → Mono/Flux using <code>Mono.fromFuture()</code> / <code>Flux.fromIterable().flatMap()</code>",
                "blocks": []
              },
              {
                "text": "<strong>Infrastructure</strong>: repository implementations use <code>CompletableFuture.supplyAsync()</code> or direct return",
                "blocks": []
              },
              {
                "text": "<strong>No reactive types in domain</strong>: Mono, Flux, DataBuffer are infrastructure-only",
                "blocks": []
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "_consequences",
        "title": "Consequences",
        "level": 2,
        "blocks": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "html": "<strong>Positive</strong>: domain stays framework-free, application layer handles the async bridge explicitly\n<strong>Negative</strong>: <code>.join()</code> in application services blocks virtual threads — acceptable for single-node"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}